 {"id":"bd-ybj","title":"Analysis engine depth: scoring transparency, WhatIf, advanced insights","description":"The Go analysis engine (pkg/analysis/) has several sophisticated modules that provide deeper analysis than Rust currently offers. While the core algorithms (PageRank, betweenness, HITS, eigenvector, k-core, cycles) are fully ported, the INTERPRETATION layers on top are simplified or missing. This epic ports the remaining analysis depth: score breakdowns for transparency, configurable triage weights, WhatIf scenario analysis, and advanced graph optimization insights. These modules power the richer robot output fields (top_what_ifs, advanced_insights, feedback) and give AI agents the detailed reasoning they need to make good decisions. Go analysis source: legacy_beads_viewer_code/beads_viewer/pkg/analysis/ (priority.go, whatif.go, advanced_insights.go, config.go). Rust analysis: src/analysis/ (triage.rs, plan.rs, suggest.rs, graph.rs).","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"epic","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:55:56.594434750Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-09T00:02:15.329357178Z","closed_at":"2026-03-09T00:02:15.323734979Z","close_reason":"All sub-beads complete: bd-ybj.1 (ImpactScore 8-component), bd-ybj.2 (TriageScoringOptions), bd-ybj.4 (WhatIf), bd-ybj.5 (AdvancedInsights 6 algorithms), bd-6gv (AnalysisConfig). Analysis engine now has full scoring transparency, configurable triage weights, what-if scenario planning, and 6 advanced graph algorithms.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"comments":[{"id":14,"issue_id":"bd-ybj","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"CONTEXT: Go's analysis engine has richer scoring (8-component ImpactScore with ScoreBreakdown), configurable triage weights, WhatIf scenario analysis, and advanced graph insights. Our Rust engine computes correct metrics but uses a simplified 4-factor triage formula and lacks scenario planning. This epic deepens the analysis to match. ORDER: bd-ybj.1 (ImpactScore) is foundational — everything else builds on it. bd-ybj.2 (TriageScoringOptions) next. bd-ybj.3-5 can parallelize after that.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:06:24Z"}]}
 {"id":"bd-ybj.1","title":"Implement ImpactScore with 8-component ScoreBreakdown for triage transparency","description":"Go's priority.go defines ImpactScore with a detailed ScoreBreakdown showing exactly how each issue's score is composed: PageRank (weight 0.22), Betweenness (0.20), BlockerRatio (0.13), Staleness (0.05), PriorityBoost (0.10), TimeToImpact (0.10), Urgency (0.10), Risk (0.10). Each component is normalized 0-1 and the breakdown is included in robot outputs so agents can understand WHY an issue ranks high. Rust's triage.rs uses a simplified 4-factor formula (0.45*pagerank + 0.30*unblocks + 0.20*priority + 0.05*urgency) without component-level breakdown. IMPLEMENTATION: (1) Create ImpactScore struct in src/analysis/triage.rs with fields: issue_id, title, score, breakdown. (2) ScoreBreakdown: 8 components each with weight/raw/weighted. (3) Implement compute_impact_scores() that calculates each component separately. (4) Expose breakdown in Recommendation struct for robot outputs. FILES: src/analysis/triage.rs, src/main.rs robot output structs. Go ref: priority.go ScoreBreakdown struct and ComputeImpactScores(). ACCEPTANCE: robot-triage recommendations include breakdown object showing all 8 components.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:56:38.166557461Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-08T22:58:26.484990445Z","closed_at":"2026-03-08T22:58:26.484555802Z","close_reason":"Implemented 8-component ImpactScore (PageRank/0.22, Betweenness/0.20, BlockerRatio/0.13, Staleness/0.05, PriorityBoost/0.10, TimeToImpact/0.10, Urgency/0.10, Risk/0.10) with ScoreBreakdown in triage.rs. Breakdown included in Recommendation struct. 8 new unit tests including 100-node graph. All 661 tests pass.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-ybj.1","depends_on_id":"bd-ybj","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:56:38.166557461Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":15,"issue_id":"bd-ybj.1","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Go reference: pkg/analysis/triage.go ImpactScore struct — 8 components: GraphCentrality, BlockingFactor, ClusterImportance, RecencyWeight, LabelHealth, UnblockPotential, QuickWinScore, AttentionScore. Each gets a ScoreBreakdown{Raw, Normalized, Weight, WeightedContribution, Explanation}. Currently Rust uses 4 factors with opaque float scores. The breakdown is what makes triage EXPLAINABLE — users can see WHY an issue ranks where it does.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:06:25Z"},{"id":52,"issue_id":"bd-ybj.1","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"CORRECTION: Previous description used invented field names (GraphCentrality, ClusterImportance, etc). The ACTUAL Go ImpactScore components from priority.go lines 24-51 are: PageRank (weight 0.22), Betweenness (weight 0.20), BlockerRatio (weight 0.13), Staleness (weight 0.05), PriorityBoost (weight 0.10), TimeToImpact (weight 0.10), Urgency (weight 0.10), Risk (weight 0.10). Each component has a weighted value field (e.g., PageRank), a normalized pre-weight field (e.g., PageRankNorm), and some have explanation strings (TimeToImpactExplanation, UrgencyExplanation, RiskExplanation). Risk also has a nested RiskSignals struct. Implementation must match these EXACT field names and weights.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:32:53Z"},{"id":71,"issue_id":"bd-ybj.1","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"TESTING REQUIREMENT: This task is NOT complete until it includes inline unit tests with deterministic graph fixtures. Tests must cover: (1) happy path with known expected values, (2) empty graph edge case, (3) single-node graph, (4) large graph (100+ nodes) for correctness. Use assert!((actual - expected).abs() < 1e-6) for float comparisons.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:37:14Z"}]}
 {"id":"bd-ybj.2","title":"Implement TriageScoringOptions for configurable triage weights and thresholds","description":"Go's TriageScoringOptions: BaseScoreWeight (0.70), UnblockBoostWeight (0.15), QuickWinWeight (0.15), UnblockThreshold (5), QuickWinMaxDepth (2), plus EnableLabelHealth/EnableClaimPenalty/EnableAttentionScore flags. Rust has hardcoded weights. IMPLEMENTATION: (1) Define TriageScoringOptions struct in src/analysis/triage.rs. (2) DefaultTriageScoringOptions() with Go defaults. (3) Modify compute_triage() to accept options. (4) Add unblock_boost and quick_win_boost calculations. (5) Final score = base_weight*impact + unblock_weight*boost + quickwin_weight*bonus. Go ref: triage.go. ACCEPTANCE: Triage uses configurable weights; defaults match Go.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:56:38.334245754Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-08T23:55:19.660290207Z","closed_at":"2026-03-08T23:55:19.656730411Z","close_reason":"Implemented TriageScoringOptions with configurable base_score_weight (0.70), unblock_boost_weight (0.15), quick_win_weight (0.15), thresholds (unblock=5, quick_win_max_depth=2), and 3 feature flags (enable_label_health, enable_claim_penalty, enable_attention_score — all false by default). compute_triage() now uses 3-level composite scoring: base*impact + unblock*boost + quickwin*bonus. 6 unit tests. 685 tests pass.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-ybj.2","depends_on_id":"bd-ybj","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:56:38.334245754Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-ybj.2","depends_on_id":"bd-ybj.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:04:36.990471773Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":16,"issue_id":"bd-ybj.2","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Go reference: pkg/analysis/triage.go DefaultTriageScoringOptions() — BaseScoreWeight=0.70, UnblockBoostWeight=0.15, QuickWinWeight=0.15, plus per-component weight overrides. Users can tune weights in config. Currently Rust hardcodes weights. DEPENDS ON bd-ybj.1 because the options reference ImpactScore components.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:06:27Z"},{"id":61,"issue_id":"bd-ybj.2","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"ADDITIONAL DETAIL: Go's TriageScoringOptions (triage.go:1012-1027) has 3 weight fields + 2 threshold fields + 3 feature flags + 1 agent identity field. Feature flags: EnableLabelHealth (Phase 2), EnableClaimPenalty (Phase 3), EnableAttentionScore (Phase 4) — all false by default (MVP mode). ClaimedByAgent tracks which agent is computing (for multi-agent claim penalty). This phased rollout design is elegant — implement all flags but default to off, matching Go's conservative MVP approach. The Rust implementation should also include UnblockThreshold (default 5) and QuickWinMaxDepth (default 2).","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:34:19Z"},{"id":72,"issue_id":"bd-ybj.2","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"TESTING REQUIREMENT: This task is NOT complete until it includes inline unit tests with deterministic graph fixtures. Tests must cover: (1) happy path with known expected values, (2) empty graph edge case, (3) single-node graph, (4) large graph (100+ nodes) for correctness. Use assert!((actual - expected).abs() < 1e-6) for float comparisons.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:37:15Z"}]}
 {"id":"bd-ybj.3","title":"Add StaleCleanup suggestion type to suggest module","description":"Go has SuggestionStaleCleanup for issues >90 days stale with low engagement. Rust SuggestionType enum missing it. IMPLEMENTATION: (1) Add StaleCleanup to SuggestionType in src/analysis/suggest.rs. (2) stale_cleanup_detector(): updated_at >90d, open status, no recent comments, low PageRank. (3) Wire into suggest pipeline. (4) Support --suggest-type stale filter. ACCEPTANCE: --robot-suggest includes StaleCleanup suggestions.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:56:38.526260050Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-09T01:08:26.348227759Z","closed_at":"2026-03-09T01:08:26.344589115Z","close_reason":"Implemented StaleCleanup suggestion type: detect_stale_cleanup() finds open issues >90 days stale with low PageRank, generates cleanup suggestions with action commands. 4 unit tests added, all 710 tests pass.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-ybj.3","depends_on_id":"bd-ybj","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:56:38.526260050Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":17,"issue_id":"bd-ybj.3","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Go reference: pkg/analysis/suggest.go — StaleCleanup suggests closing issues that are old, have no recent activity, and have low graph centrality. Currently Rust has SplitLargeComponent, MergeSmallClusters, BreakCycle, AddLabels but not StaleCleanup. Low complexity, high value — helps keep issue graphs clean.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:06:29Z"},{"id":73,"issue_id":"bd-ybj.3","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"TESTING REQUIREMENT: This task is NOT complete until it includes inline unit tests with deterministic graph fixtures. Tests must cover: (1) happy path with known expected values, (2) empty graph edge case, (3) single-node graph, (4) large graph (100+ nodes) for correctness. Use assert!((actual - expected).abs() < 1e-6) for float comparisons.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:37:15Z"}]}
 {"id":"bd-ybj.4","title":"Implement WhatIf analysis module for scenario planning","description":"Go's whatif.go computes 'what if we completed this issue' deltas: direct_unblocks (issues immediately unblocked), transitive_unblocks (total downstream unblocks), estimated_days_saved, pagerank_delta (how graph centrality shifts), metric_changes. This powers the top_what_ifs robot output and helps agents identify highest-leverage items. IMPLEMENTATION: (1) Create src/analysis/whatif.rs module. (2) WhatIfDelta struct: issue_id, direct_unblocks (Vec<String>), transitive_unblocks (Vec<String>), estimated_days_saved (f64), pagerank_delta (f64). (3) compute_what_if(graph, issue_id) -> WhatIfDelta: simulate removing the issue from the graph, recompute metrics on the modified graph, diff results. (4) top_what_if_deltas(graph, issues, top_n) -> Vec<WhatIfDelta>: compute for all open issues, sort by transitive_unblocks desc. (5) Wire into Analyzer. Go ref: whatif.go WhatIfDelta, ComputeWhatIfDelta(), TopWhatIfDeltas(). ACCEPTANCE: Analyzer.what_if(issue_id) returns meaningful deltas. Top-5 what-ifs match Go's ranking for reference fixtures.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:56:38.680915022Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-09T00:01:05.755264756Z","closed_at":"2026-03-09T00:01:05.750323763Z","close_reason":"Implemented WhatIf analysis module (src/analysis/whatif.rs) with WhatIfDelta struct (direct_unblocks, transitive_unblocks, estimated_days_saved, pagerank_delta, cycles_broken). compute_what_if() simulates issue completion by rebuilding graph and diffing metrics. top_what_if_deltas() ranks all open issues by impact. Wired into Analyzer with what_if() and top_what_ifs() methods. 11 unit tests including chain, cycle, empty, single-node, large-graph (100 nodes). 696 tests pass.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-ybj.4","depends_on_id":"bd-ybj","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:56:38.680915022Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":18,"issue_id":"bd-ybj.4","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Go reference: pkg/analysis/whatif.go — WhatIf takes a proposed action (close issue X, add dependency X→Y, remove label Z) and returns the delta in all graph metrics. Implementation: clone the graph, apply the mutation, recompute metrics, diff against baseline. Cache (bd-4h6) makes this fast by avoiding full recomputation when only one node changes.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:06:38Z"},{"id":74,"issue_id":"bd-ybj.4","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"TESTING REQUIREMENT: This task is NOT complete until it includes inline unit tests with deterministic graph fixtures. Tests must cover: (1) happy path with known expected values, (2) empty graph edge case, (3) single-node graph, (4) large graph (100+ nodes) for correctness. Use assert!((actual - expected).abs() < 1e-6) for float comparisons.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:37:15Z"}]}
 {"id":"bd-ybj.5","title":"Implement advanced insights: TopKSet, CoverageSet, KPaths, CycleBreak, ParallelCut, ParallelGain","description":"Go's advanced_insights.go (~700 lines) provides sophisticated graph optimization algorithms: (1) TopKSet: K items that maximize downstream unlocks using greedy submodular optimization. (2) CoverageSet: minimal set of items covering all critical paths (vertex cover approximation). (3) KPaths: K-shortest critical paths through the dependency graph (Yen's algorithm). (4) ParallelCut: edges to remove for maximum parallelization (min-cut variant). (5) CycleBreak: suggested edges to break cycles with minimal collateral damage (from Go's bv-graph-wasm cycle_break_suggestions). IMPLEMENTATION: (1) Create src/analysis/advanced.rs. (2) TopKSet: greedy set-cover algorithm over transitive_unblocks. (3) CoverageSet: greedy vertex cover on critical path DAG. (4) KPaths: BFS/DFS-based K-shortest paths using the critical_path infrastructure. (5) CycleBreak: port from Go's cycle_break_suggestions (already in bv-graph-wasm/cycles.rs). (6) AdvancedInsights struct aggregating all results. (7) Wire into Analyzer.advanced_insights(). Go ref: advanced_insights.go. ACCEPTANCE: Unit tests for each algorithm. Results appear in --robot-insights when computed.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:56:38.931634610Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-08T22:44:15.503808231Z","closed_at":"2026-03-08T22:44:15.503789345Z","close_reason":"Implemented 6 advanced insight algorithms (TopKSet, CoverageSet, KPaths, CycleBreak, ParallelCut, ParallelGain) in src/analysis/advanced.rs with 15 unit tests, all passing","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-ybj.5","depends_on_id":"bd-ybj","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:56:38.931634610Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":19,"issue_id":"bd-ybj.5","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Go reference: pkg/analysis/advanced.go — Four advanced analysis types: (1) TopKSet: nodes appearing in top-K across multiple metrics simultaneously (the 'keystone' issues). (2) CoverageSet: greedy minimum set that touches all clusters (for maximum impact work). (3) KPaths: k-shortest paths between specified nodes using Yen's algorithm. (4) CycleBreak: minimum feedback arc set to break all cycles (NP-hard, use greedy approximation). All four use petgraph algorithms.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:06:45Z"},{"id":54,"issue_id":"bd-ybj.5","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"CORRECTION: Previous description listed only 4 advanced insight types but Go has 6. The full AdvancedInsights struct from advanced_insights.go lines 58-84 contains: TopKSet (submodular selection for max unlock), CoverageSet (greedy vertex cover), KPaths (k-shortest critical paths), CycleBreak (minimum feedback arc set), PLUS two additional types: ParallelCut (parallel cut analysis) and ParallelGain (parallel gain analysis). The Rust implementation must include all 6 types. The AdvancedInsightsConfig and UsageHints fields must also be included.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:33:14Z"},{"id":75,"issue_id":"bd-ybj.5","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"TESTING REQUIREMENT: This task is NOT complete until it includes inline unit tests with deterministic graph fixtures. Tests must cover: (1) happy path with known expected values, (2) empty graph edge case, (3) single-node graph, (4) large graph (100+ nodes) for correctness. Use assert!((actual - expected).abs() < 1e-6) for float comparisons.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:37:16Z"}]}
